 And her reaction to everything.

55
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:20,000
 Uh, what is the temperament?

56
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 Mm-hmm.

57
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 What is the character?

58
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 Mm-hmm.

59
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 What are all those things in identity?

60
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 How the person is formed?

61
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 Mm-hmm.

62
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 Well, we can think about identity in several different ways.

63
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 And I remember when I came to my mentor at one point when I was submitting for my graduate thesis,

64
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 and I was like, I want to do a thesis that's about identity and entrepreneurship.

65
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 And I want to connect the two.

66
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 And she's like, okay, what is identity?

67
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
 How you're going to define it?

68
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 How you're going to measure it?

69
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,000
 What is going to be in the questionnaire?

70
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:59,000
 I was like, oh, okay.

71
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 Now we have a lot of loaded questions.

72
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:12,000
 And then I started looking into things and I noticed that there's so many different ways that we can actually define identity.

73
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 We can say, and that's one of the theories.

74
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 It says, hey, identity is a set of characteristics and behaviors and expressions that a person or a group has.

75
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 Awesome.

76
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 And then there is this other theory that says, well, yeah, but it's also about social belonging and which groups do you kind of go with or get along with.

77
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 So it's about interchange between those groups.

78
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 Oh, awesome.

79
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 Then there is the third theory, which says, well, it can be about your past and the way that your past shaped you.

80
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 And it can be about the present, which is who am I and how do I experience myself at this moment.

81
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 But then there is also about the future.

82
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 So who exactly am I becoming?

83
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 And then it can be about the place and the physical, literal moment that we are now.

84
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 So am I different if I'm in New York or if I'm in a desert or if I'm from a small village in Croatia?

85
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 And then you kind of start to understand it's complicated and it's complex.

86
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:21,000
 And that's where the beauty is.

87
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:26,000
 I remembered one of your writings.

88
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:30,000
 You said that you are curious about curiosity.

89
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 And I can see right now why I'm very similar.

90
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,000
 Very similar.

91
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 So if we talk about who am I, about identity, as I'm a really hobbyist, also philosopher, but also psychologist.

92
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 I do it as a hobby.

93
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:56,000
 I like it.

94
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 I have the interest in it.

95
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 So when we are talking about this, who am I?

96
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:18,000
 And people tend to tell me, authors or people around me, that self-awareness is one of the most important things in life.

97
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 Because if you are more self-aware, you will have better quality of life, you can get along better with yourself and the people around you.

98
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:36,000
 You will know your faults, you will know your strengths and things like that.

99
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:51,000
 So when we are talking about those things, about identity and who am I, how are we going to connect it with self-awareness?

100
00:11:51,000 --> 00:12:01,000
 So how, do you have some techniques, tools that you use to become more self-aware than you were 10 years ago?

101
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 For sure.

102
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:09,000
 How to be more self-aware when this is a peeling the onion type of question, who am I?

103
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 I will tell you an anecdote first.

104
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:21,000
 So I was back home maybe two or three years ago or something like that.

105
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 And I was with my mom shopping for, I don't know, detergents or something.

106
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 And at one point we met my professor from high school.

107
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
 And she looked at me and she was like up and down.

108
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 She's like, you're different.

109
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:50,000
 And it was in that moment, like that surprise that got me really thinking, yes, I am different, but I'm not working on myself to stay the same.

110
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 And this is where I believe self-awareness comes in.

111
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 It's about, first of all, in my experience and in the experience of my clients, it's about slowing down.

112
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:13,000
 We cannot change something that we are not able to recognize or something that we feel extreme resistance towards.

113
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:17,000
 We need to allow for change to happen.

114
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:28,000
 I feel that when we are becoming somebody other than who we are, so we are making different choices and we want to create those different experiences.

115
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 It's not about becoming more of something.

116
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:39,000
 We want to be more beautiful, more smart, more educated, more worthy.

117
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 It's usually about becoming less, about losing the expectations of other people, about losing some societal norms or losing whatever we thought we were supposed to be doing at a given moment.

118
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 Or losing our ideal perfection or our ideal version or how we are supposed to be.

119
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 I think that is where self-awareness comes in.

120
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 I already am enough.

121
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
 I already am beautiful, smart, educated.

122
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,000
 All of those things.

123
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 We will come to that question later.

124
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 I have one question in my mind right now, but we will postpone it.

125
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:37,000
 Can you give to the audience some of the techniques or tools that you can use to improve your self-awareness?

126
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 I know this is going to sound like such a cliche, but slowing down or even better stopping for a moment.

127
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:50,000
 I love the technique of boxed breathing.

128
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 I don't know, have you ever heard about it?

129
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 Yes.

130
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:57,000
 Maybe somebody from the audience hasn't, so I will kind of summarize it very quickly.

131
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:13,000
 It is essentially when we breathe in for four seconds and then we stop for four seconds and then we breathe out for four seconds and then stop for four seconds and we repeat the process.

132
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 And what happens in that process is that we are able to isolate or even ignore some of our thoughts and we realize that we are more than the thoughts that are running in our mind.

133
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,000
 That slowness really brings clarity.

134
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 People can also try with meditation.

135
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 Sometimes we can go with guided meditation.

136
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:40,000
 It's a great start.

137
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:53,000
 But I would also advise that or say that meditation doesn't have to be this cumbersome process that we are trying to get better at every day.

138
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:03,000
 We can literally just be sitting on the floor or standing or sitting on a chair with our feet on the floor, focusing on our breathing and that's it.

139
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:10,000
 Because even sometimes the guided meditation can become the distraction, you know.

140
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:14,000
 I am also a huge fan of journaling.

141
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:18,000
 Whenever I have a lot of confusion in my mind, I will just sit down.

142
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 I will write it out.

143
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:26,000
 And in some cases, and this is the experience of people that I have been working with.

144
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:38,000
 The block comes from thinking, well, how do I phrase this in a specific or certain way so that the other person or whoever is, quote unquote, supposed to read it better understands it.

145
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 But it's not about writing it for another human being.

146
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:44,000
 It's about writing it for yourself.

147
00:16:44,000 --> 00:17:01,000
 So what would you write if you were writing to gain clarity, to allow yourself that everything that's currently filling you with anger or confusion or sadness or I mean, I literally sometimes cried over a piece of paper.

148
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 And that release coming from it's everything stays on the paper.

149
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:07,000
 And that's beautiful.

150
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 So, yes, there are other techniques and we can find resolution or peace in them.

151
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:23,000
 I'm always saying that meditation can be going for groceries and, you know, kind of shopping for cucumbers.

152
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:24,000
 It doesn't have to be super complicated.

153
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 It can be running at 6pm when there are no mosquitoes and it can be swimming.

154
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:44,000
 It can be, you know, whatever it is, but it is the mindfulness that we bring to the process that makes the experience cleansing for us.

155
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:45,000
 Very good ideas.

156
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:46,000
 Very good ideas.

157
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:47,000
 Thank you.

158
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:48,000
 Thank you.

159
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:49,000
 Thank you so much.

160
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:58,000
 So, you said box printing, you said meditation, whether guided or unguided.

161
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 You said running, you said a lot of other interesting things, journaling also.

162
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:11,000
 I journal for a long time.

163
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,000
 I think that I started 2011.

164
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 So, it's 11 years at the moment.

165
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:31,000
 But what I also included in my journaling is the habit of continually rereading what I wrote.

166
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:40,000
 So, I learned about it, I'm not sure from who, but very, very long ago.

167
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 And what I do, I must confess, I don't do it that regularly anymore.

168
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 But whenever I have the need to do, I do it.

169
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:58,000
 I reread my journals every week, every Sunday.

170
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:04,000
 Whatever I wrote, if I wrote a few sentences, I reread them.

171
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:07,000
 And I make a conclusion on Sunday.

172
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:15,000
 Then, on the end of the month, I reread those Sundays and make another conclusion.

173
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:20,000
 And when the end of the year comes, then I read everything as a book.

174
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:23,000
 That is such a great idea.

175
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:29,000
 And then, I say, okay, Winko, what are we going to do next year?

176
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:38,000
 And, but this is a good technique because usually we do this only once a year.

177
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 It's a New Year's, and we have our resolutions.

178
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:48,000
 But if you do it regularly, then you can change or tweak some things on time, not to postpone them.

179
00:19:48,000 --> 00:20:00,000
 But a good thing is when you read your journal from the last year in one bite in one week, for example, then some things tend to pop up on the surface.

180
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:03,000
 And you say, hmm, this is repeating.

181
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:05,000
 Let's see.

182
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 That is such a good idea.

183
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 When we are regularly tracking our thoughts and emotions associated with specific thoughts and situations, then we are able to identify, oh, look, it's interesting.

184
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 Whenever I'm living through a specific situation or whenever I am with a specific person or whenever X, Y, Z is happening, I get the same reaction.

185
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,000
 I am repeating something.

186
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:36,000
 The behavior is the same.

187
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,000
 The feeling is the same.

188
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:43,000
 And this is the self-awareness that you have been talking about and you keep asking me about.

189
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:56,000
 This is the moment where, look, sometimes when we look at our year in reverse, we as humans beings, we tend to forget what caused specific feelings.

190
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:00,000
 And we were like, well, it was fine.

191
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:04,000
 And that's why people stay in unhappy relationships.

192
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,000
 And that's why they don't change jobs.

193
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 Because at the end of the year, nothing is that bad.

194
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:13,000
 We just have three glasses of champagne and we party it out.

195
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:27,000
 But when you're tracking things, I sometimes feel that people don't want to do different things because they are more scared of succeeding than a failure.

196
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 Definitely.

197
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 Because failure is familiar to them or being average or fitting in.

198
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:40,000
 So this is why.

199
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:41,000
 Okay.

200
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:43,000
 Let's go a little bit further.

201
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:45,000
 Who am I?

