 They're maybe not going to psychotherapy.

211
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:21,000
 They're maybe not doing coaching.

212
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:22,000
 Mm-hmm.

213
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,000
 They're going, having a coach.

214
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:25,000
 Mm-hmm.

215
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 They're not, I don't know, meditating, whatever.

216
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:28,000
 But they are improving themselves.

217
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:44,000
 And when we talk all about those things, I learned still that there is one part of me that

218
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 is still the same as a child I was when I was five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten years old.

219
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:52,000
 Mm-hmm.

220
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 How are you going to explain that?

221
00:22:57,000 --> 00:22:58,000
 Mm-hmm.

222
00:22:58,000 --> 00:22:59,000
 You know, we are changing.

223
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 Mm-hmm.

224
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:01,000
 Our environment is changing.

225
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:03,000
 Our locations are changing.

226
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 Mm-hmm.

227
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:05,000
 Whatever.

228
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:07,000
 Uh, we are growing, definitely.

229
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:08,000
 Mm-hmm.

230
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:09,000
 We are learning.

231
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:10,000
 Mm-hmm.

232
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:15,000
 But somehow, I think, I see it in my daughter.

233
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:16,000
 She's nine months old.

234
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 Mm-hmm.

235
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:20,000
 But I see who she is already.

236
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:21,000
 Mm-hmm.

237
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:22,000
 Mm-hmm.

238
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:25,000
 It doesn't matter what she will learn in life.

239
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:27,000
 I know who she is right now.

240
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:31,000
 And I feel about myself the same.

241
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:32,000
 Mm-hmm.

242
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:34,000
 I knew who I was when I was five, ten.

243
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:35,000
 Mm-hmm.

244
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:36,000
 I'm still the same.

245
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:37,000
 Mm-hmm.

246
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 I just changed on the, some tools, techniques, reactions.

247
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:45,000
 But on the, in the core, I'm the same.

248
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:47,000
 Do you think this is true?

249
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:48,000
 Absolutely.

250
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:55,000
 Um, this is part of, I would say, more of a philosophy rather than psychology.

251
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:59,000
 But I feel that core is actually who we are.

252
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:04,000
 I believe it was Eckhart Tolle who said that you are not your thoughts.

253
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:06,000
 You are the observer of your thoughts.

254
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:11,000
 And the irony lies in the fact, as soon as you recognize that, it kind of escapes you.

255
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 You know?

256
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:16,000
 Like, you cannot say, oh, now I see this person underneath.

257
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:18,000
 I can see my core.

258
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:19,000
 No.

259
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:26,000
 Like, whatever it is inside, and we can call it light, and we can call it soul, and we can call it purpose.

260
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:31,000
 And, you know, like there are bold things and names out there.

261
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:35,000
 But in the end, that's what drives you.

262
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 That's what kind of propels you forward.

263
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,000
 And you can accept it, and you can allow it.

264
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:53,000
 And the more that you accept and allow it, the more, and I will use this word that keeps on floating up in every conversation that I have, it's being more authentic.

265
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 What does that even mean?

266
00:24:56,000 --> 00:24:57,000
 Yes.

267
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:00,000
 What does it mean?

268
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:18,000
 I suppose that it means, when we talk about ego, my definition is, how I interpret it to myself is, all of those things that we put on ourselves to get along with the society.

269
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:19,000
 Mm-hmm.

270
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 This is the ego.

271
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:26,000
 And our authentic self is, is, is Ivana from five years old, or 10 years old.

272
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:27,000
 Mm-hmm.

273
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:33,000
 This, this means, so that you don't, that you are not afraid of what others will think.

274
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:34,000
 Mm-hmm.

275
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:37,000
 That you don't try to fit in.

276
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:38,000
 Mm-hmm.

277
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:41,000
 That you don't want to hurt anybody, but you're not trying to fit in.

278
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:42,000
 Mm-hmm.

279
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:43,000
 Mm-hmm.

280
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 You just want to express yourself.

281
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 Mm-hmm.

282
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:46,000
 Who you are.

283
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:49,000
 Mm-hmm.

284
00:25:49,000 --> 00:26:08,000
 In a way, I feel there is so much conditioning going on for every single human being on the planet, whether that's, be a good girl, or be a boy who doesn't cry, or be smart, or be a valuable member of the society, or whatever it is.

285
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:16,000
 And parents, or caretakers, they don't say that because they want to F us up, to be very clear.

286
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:24,000
 It's just that sometimes their best intentions are not necessarily how we want our life to play out.

287
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 You know, I think one of the best phases in life of a kid is, they're usually around two or three years old, they learn how to speak, I say something and the world responds, but they still don't have the filter of what's appropriate.

288
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 You know, like, oh, happy birthday, mom, you're one year older, are you going to get ugly now, or whatever it is, you know.

289
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:54,000
 And I remember kids saying things like that, where they're not thinking about what they say, this is their truth.

290
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:06,000
 And I'm not saying that we should be going through life offending people, but I'm saying that we should allow ourselves to, for that part within, to speak through us.

291
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:16,000
 You know, like through all of the conditioning to, like, do you know how kids sometimes get very curious about, well, why does this work like this?

292
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 When are we going to get there? How much time is there left for XYZ? They keep asking questions, and they don't stop until they actually get the answer.

293
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 Daddy, why is the sky blue? Well, because blah, blah, blah. Okay, so when does, but daddy, the sky is not blue all the time.

294
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:44,000
 And then another set of questions. And then eventually, most of the dads are going to get very upset and say, the sky is blue, because the sky is blue.

295
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:57,000
 Because I say so. Because I say so. But what would happen if we allowed ourselves to be as curious as we were when we were kids?

296
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:03,000
 I'm that curious, but I don't want to bother people with my questions. This is why I have a podcast.

297
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:05,000
 Yes. So I can ask questions.

298
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:07,000
 It's a channeled curiosity.

299
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:12,000
 Yes, yes, yes. I have an alibi to ask questions.

300
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:29,000
 So we were talking about who am I, identity, self-awareness. Maybe we will go a little bit further. And I will ask you, what is a mindset?

301
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:40,000
 Is mindset somehow attached to identity? What is a mindset? Everybody is speaking about the mindset.

302
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 Yeah.

303
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:48,000
 You need to have mindset like this, like that. You need to be strong. You need to be productive. You need to believe in yourself. You need that.

304
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:50,000
 What is mindset?

305
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:51,000
 Well.

306
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,000
 And what is a growth mindset? If you're familiar with the term.

307
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:04,000
 Yeah. Yes, I am. It was one of the first things that we learned when I was in ISEC, the global organization for student exchange.

308
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:19,000
 One of the first things they told us, people who want to grow, they need to have a growth mindset. And I remember having these little blop, blop, blop, blop, blop above my head thinking, well, what in the world is that?

309
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:27,000
 And then I learned, okay, growth mindset is when you allow for change and when you are curious about how things can be different.

310
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 When you believe that you can change.

311
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:31,000
 Yes. Yes.

312
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:32,000
 You believe.

313
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:33,000
 100%.

314
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:47,000
 And one of the things that I strongly believe is that our perception of who we are is the filter that shapes our mindset.

315
00:29:47,000 --> 00:30:04,000
 So if we believe that, let's say, I'm a person who can only work nine to five for the rest of my life, and I am the best team player, and this is how my life will play out, then that's it for you.

316
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:08,000
 Because you don't believe another possibility is out there.

317
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:11,000
 So identity is driving mindset.

318
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:12,000
 In a way.

319
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:13,000
 In a way.

320
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:14,000
 Yeah.

321
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:15,000
 I would say so.

322
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:23,000
 I think that those filters and filters are very closely connected to identity.

323
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:30,000
 Because if I say, I am a woman, I am 30 years old, I am creation.

324
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:31,000
 I am a lesbian.

325
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:33,000
 I am in a partnership.

326
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:36,000
 I am earning XYZ.

327
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 I am a coach.

328
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:43,000
 I am whatever it is, whatever label we put on ourselves.

329
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:48,000
 We look for other things that will be the recognition of that.

330
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 What is possible for people that have those labels?

331
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:02,000
 And our identity, and those different labels that we put on there, actually will shape that filter.

332
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:06,000
 Oh, okay, I see what's happening there.

333
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:17,000
 So a woman of my age, of my status, of my appearance, of my expression, of my education, these are the things that are possible for her.

334
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:22,000
 So our mindset, yes, it definitely becomes shaped by who we are.

335
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:30,000
 And then again, it can change if we are curious about other things outside of those labels.

336
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:41,000
 I sometimes say to my clients, and I definitely said it to myself, you don't need 17 different proofs that different is possible.

337
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:43,000
 You need only one.

338
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:58,000
 So if I find one person who is, let's say, not working nine to five, but works three hours per week and earns, I don't know, bajillion of monies, then I'm going to believe that is possible because I have proof.

339
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:03,000
 And let us not get confused, people love proof.

340
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:07,000
 We can say, oh, I believe this is possible for me.

341
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:08,000
 I know that I can do it.

342
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:22,000
 And this is what startup founders do, you know, but it's so much easier when that person can say, you know what, I'm dropping from Harvard because Steve Jobs or whoever it was already did that.

343
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:24,000
 So I know this is possible for me as well.

344
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:27,000
 You know, like, it's a connection thing.

345
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:28,000
 Oh, yeah.

346
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:29,000
 You're absolutely right.

347
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:39,000
 It's the famous four mile rule when the first person hit the four mile.

348
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:40,000
 Yes.

349
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:42,000
 No, one mile under the four minutes.

350
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:43,000
 Sorry.

351
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:44,000
 Yes.

352
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:50,000
 Then suddenly, dozens, hundreds and thousands and millions of people did it after him.

353
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:51,000
 Yeah.

354
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:52,000
 So this is very interesting.

355
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:53,000
 Yeah.

356
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:54,000
 Yeah.

357
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:55,000
 Yeah.

358
00:32:55,000 --> 00:33:03,000
 Uh, so it's a pity that I had a friend, unfortunately.

359
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:04,000
 Uh, he passed away.

360
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:09,000
 Uh, I was, uh, having a lot of talks with him about his mindset.

361
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:20,000
 Uh, he was, uh, a person that you can see on him that he had a fixed mindset.

362
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:21,000
 Mm-hmm.

363
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:26,000
 He thought that he is as he is and then he cannot change.

364
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:27,000
 Mm-hmm.

365
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:29,000
 And he didn't want to do it.

366
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:31,000
 He didn't want to fight for it.

367
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:32,000
 Mm-hmm.

368
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:33,000
 Mm-hmm.

369
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:34,000
 This is who I am.

370
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:35,000
 Accept me.

371
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:36,000
 Mm-hmm.

372
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:44,000
 He's, he was trying to accept himself, but he, he really thought that he was stuck.

373
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:45,000
 Mm-hmm.

374
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:48,000
 Uh, with, with, uh, everything that he had.

375
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:49,000
 Mm-hmm.

376
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:51,000
 That he cannot change and, or improve.

377
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:54,000
 But, uh, when we are talking about it.

378
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:56,000
 Can I just add something?

379
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:57,000
 Mm-hmm.

380
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:05,000
 Um, one of the things that I hear people say so often, or better yet, make it two.

381
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:10,000
 Is, the first one is, I am the way that I am.

382
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:13,000
 You know, it's kind of take it or leave it situation.

383
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:16,000
 And they don't believe that they can change.

384
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:23,000
 And, at that point, I always love asking them, oh, okay.

385
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:29,000
 But if a tree can change, does that make you less than a tree?

386
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:33,000
 Everything is able to change in nature.

387
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:34,000
 So are you.

388
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:40,000
 And then, there's this other thing that people love saying, and it's extremely popular.

389
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:43,000
 And that other thing is, you know what?

390
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:46,000
 When X changes, then I will.

391
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:50,000
 So, if I have more money, then I will invest in education.

392
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:59,000
 Or, if, or when I have a partner, then I will be going to, I don't know, museums, or countryside,

393
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:01,000
 or whatever it is.

394
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:09,000
 We believe that something outside of us has greater power than something inside of us.

395
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:12,000
 And we look for that safety somewhere else.

396
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:15,000
 And that is the problem.

397
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:18,000
 The safety always comes from within.

398
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:24,000
 And yes, sometimes other people will not be able to reciprocate that.

399
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:32,000
 But that doesn't mean that your desires, or your goals, or your dreams, or your expression is less worthy.

400
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:38,000
 It just means that those people have a different outlook on life.

401
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:40,000
 And this is an extremely important phrase.

402
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:48,000
 Because we love thinking that, well, if somebody doesn't agree with me, then they are to blame.

403
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:51,000
 We love looking for a guilty party.

404
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:55,000
 And sometimes, it's just that the experience is different.

405
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:06,000
 The magical part is, when you are who you are, you don't have to think about who likes it.

406
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:09,000
 And what did you say to that person?

407
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:10,000
 On which occasion?

408
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:13,000
 And which role are you playing right now?

409
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:16,000
 You just get to be yourself.

410
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:31,000
 And then, in that magic, you invite the right people, and the right jobs, and the right opportunities, and whatever is "right for you".

411
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:43,000
 Lately, I was saying often, relationships are one of the hottest things to do.

412
00:36:43,000 --> 00:37:00,000
 I'm not thinking only about relationships with a loved one, with your partner, but relationships in work environment, with friends.

413
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:18,000
 And then, I know that what I think, what I say, will finally be presented in my behavior, and in my results.

414
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:28,000
 And then, I bite my tongue, and I said, "Why am I saying this out loud? I need to stop saying this, that relationships are hard."

415
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:33,000
 And then, relationships will be hard for me, if I say it.

416
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:47,000
 So, with this question, how to improve yourself right now, or how can you improve yourself right now, let's try to talk a little bit about this process.

417
00:37:47,000 --> 00:38:08,000
 First, it comes the thought in our mind, then we say it, then it starts to become our behavior, and it is a cycle, we get emotion, we reaffirm this emotion, and we have, again, thought, behavior, and this never-ending cycle.

418
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:13,000
 So, why is it important to track what you think and what you say?

419
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:18,000
 I love saying, why would you choose that thought?

420
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:27,000
 But I was not aware of this thought, I was not aware. I was saying it, relationships are hard.

421
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:33,000
 I didn't even think how this would affect my relationships, if I say relationships are hard.

422
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:37,000
 Okay, I was thinking that you are aware of that.

423
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:46,000
 I was being aware that, because I see it around myself, that people get into conflicts a lot, you know.

424
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:47,000
 Yeah.

425
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:50,000
 When I say something, I can hurt you. When you say something, you can hurt me.

426
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:59,000
 Then you have group dynamics, you have all kinds of flavors of relationship.

427
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:07,000
 And I was believing this so, this is so, that relationships are hard, because I see it around myself.

428
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:11,000
 But then I said, this is not going to be a truth for me.

429
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:15,000
 I will stop saying it, I will stop thinking it, I will stop believing it.

430
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:17,000
 Okay.

431
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:22,000
 Well, I think the answer is twofold.

432
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:29,000
 First, we go back to what we were already talking about, becoming aware of a thought that we are having.

433
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:32,000
 And we can do that in a number of ways.

434
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:43,000
 But then the other part of the puzzle comes in, where we, in that moment of stopping or slowing down at least,

435
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:52,000
 where we do have to think and discuss with ourselves first, why am I choosing to think this?

436
00:39:52,000 --> 00:40:02,000
 People sometimes act like, it's almost like we are mad at a certain part of ourselves.

437
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:06,000
 It's almost like, why am I doing this to myself?

438
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:12,000
 But whatever we are thinking, it is serving us in one way or the other.

439
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:21,000
