00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:49,000
 then we can see what changes will occur, you know?

691
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:52,000
 So, for example, I don't watch TV.

692
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:55,000
 And people always tell me I live in a happy bubble.

693
00:55:55,000 --> 00:55:59,000
 Like, I am not unaware of how the world works,

694
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:11,000
 but why would I consciously expose myself to XYZ media that is going to fill my mind with things that are out of my control?

695
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:13,000
 So I have this rule.

696
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:23,000
 If something bothers me, I will either stop worrying about it or I will do something about it.

697
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:29,000
 And like 95% of the things, it just doesn't bother me that much, you know?

698
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:37,000
 So, yeah, maybe it's about I'm not I'm not sure what is the correct answer for every single person that is listening.

699
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:53,000
 But I can say that you can start by seeing, hey, am I following the accounts on social media that are fueling my sense of self and my values or they are fueling my insecurities?

700
00:56:53,000 --> 00:57:04,000
 If you're looking at pictures of, I don't know, Kim Kardashian and thinking, my body is so bad or I should be richer or I should be in a happier relationship.

701
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:10,000
 Like, my brother is 26 years now.

702
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:14,000
 And he's like, I thought I was going to be married by now.

703
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:19,000
 Like, oh, OK, but you're not actually going out meeting people.

704
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:33,000
 So I think that one of the things that people very often underestimate are the people that I actually they are surrounded with.

705
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:38,000
 So who are the five people that you spend your time with?

706
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:40,000
 How do you spend that time with them?

707
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:41,000
 Are you arguing?

708
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:42,000
 Are you negotiating?

709
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:44,000
 Are you compromising yourself?

710
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:52,000
 Are those people inviting you into something that is possible for you?

711
00:57:52,000 --> 00:57:56,000
 Are they inviting you to reconsider specific things?

712
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:01,000
 Are they inviting you to explore yourself and life?

713
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:07,000
 I love that phrase being invited into fullness, giving yourself grace.

714
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:08,000
 Are those people.

715
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:09,000
 Are those people.

716
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:10,000
 What does it mean?

717
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:11,000
 Being invited in the fullness.

718
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:12,000
 Into your fullness.

719
00:58:12,000 --> 00:58:13,000
 Yeah.

720
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:14,000
 Into your fullness.

721
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:15,000
 Fullness.

722
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:16,000
 Yeah.

723
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:17,000
 How would you describe it?

724
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:18,000
 Fullness.

725
00:58:18,000 --> 00:58:19,000
 What does it mean?

726
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:20,000
 Can you give us a second example?

727
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:21,000
 For me, yeah.

728
00:58:21,000 --> 00:58:30,000
 For me, it means not apologizing for the way that you behave, operate and feel in life.

729
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:33,000
 You don't have to compromise parts of yourself.

730
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:35,000
 You don't have to dim your light.

731
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:40,000
 You know, like if you have an opinion about something, you're going to share it freely.

732
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:45,000
 You are going to speak your truth, even if it's a little bit inconvenient.

733
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:51,000
 You're not trying to manage other people emotions by suppressing your thoughts.

734
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:55,000
 You are clear about voicing your boundaries.

735
00:58:55,000 --> 00:58:58,000
 Those people respect them.

736
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:07,000
 It's a beautiful dynamic where you're not protecting people from the consequences of their actions.

737
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:11,000
 You're responsible for yourself and the other person is too.

738
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:24,000
 You know what I want to ask you right now is to work on yourself.

739
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:27,000
 It's a long process.

740
00:59:27,000 --> 00:59:30,000
 It's a lifelong process.

741
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:34,000
 It's hard to measure it.

742
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:40,000
 The only person that can measure it are with ourselves.

743
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:43,000
 So it's a subjective measure.

744
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:50,000
 But if we feel better, if we feel that the quality of our life is better, then we are right.

745
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:53,000
 That's why it's important to have a good measuring stick.

746
00:59:53,000 --> 00:59:55,000
 Yes, yes.

747
00:59:55,000 --> 01:00:05,000
 And we can use several techniques.

748
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:11,000
 We can really work on ourselves diligently, continuously for years, for decades.

749
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:30,000
 And sometimes I have this feeling sometimes that somehow it seems to me that I didn't change, that it's going, that it's too hard.

750
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:31,000
 Mm-hmm.

751
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:40,000
 That I think about it, write about it, try to implement it in my life.

752
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:44,000
 And sometimes I see I just didn't do it.

753
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:48,000
 I didn't transfer it into my behavior.

754
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:49,000
 Yes.

755
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:55,000
 So the question is, how can we truly, truly, truly transform ourselves?

756
01:00:55,000 --> 01:01:01,000
 How can we truly change our behavior?

757
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:02,000
 Mm-hmm.

758
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:11,000
 For example, I want to be more confident or I want to be more clear communicator.

759
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:18,000
 I want to, but I still find myself to catch myself that I still don't communicate clearly.

760
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:19,000
 I still don't.

761
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:23,000
 And I'm working on it for several years.

762
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:24,000
 Mm-hmm.

763
01:01:24,000 --> 01:01:26,000
 How to truly transform?

764
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:31,000
 Well, in that question, I actually hear a little bit of perfectionism.

765
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:32,000
 Truly.

766
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:33,000
 Here.

767
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:37,000
 Yes, I'm perfectionist 101.

768
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:43,000
 I know it's because I was doing self-exploration.

769
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:44,000
 Yeah.

770
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:54,000
 And I know when I got, when I get over, when the perfection gets all over me, gets all

771
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:59,000
 over me, so I can sense it and I can say, okay, stop.

772
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:00,000
 Mm-hmm.

773
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:02,000
 So how to truly transform?

774
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:04,000
 There is no D answer.

775
01:02:04,000 --> 01:02:06,000
 There is no D answer.

776
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:07,000
 It's a pity.

777
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:08,000
 Yeah, it is.

778
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:09,000
 It's a pity.

779
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:10,000
 It's not so good.

780
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:11,000
 Mm-hmm.

781
01:02:11,000 --> 01:02:17,000
 Because that means that there is no secret recipe that anyone is hiding from you.

782
01:02:17,000 --> 01:02:18,000
 Mm-hmm.

783
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:19,000
 Because nobody has the recipe.

784
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:20,000
 Exactly.

785
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:21,000
 Exactly.

786
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:22,000
 Mm-hmm.

787
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:24,000
 You just go at it.

788
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:30,000
 What would you do if you just wanted to make this path fun for you?

789
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:41,000
 Can I say then that self-improvement or personal development, self-exploration, they are somehow

790
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:46,000
 ruining our life, ruining our peace?

791
01:02:46,000 --> 01:02:49,000
 It's a bold, bold phrase that you just used.

792
01:02:49,000 --> 01:02:50,000
 Is it?

793
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:51,000
 Yeah.

794
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:53,000
 Can it ruin our life?

795
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:54,000
 Yes, if we look.

796
01:02:54,000 --> 01:02:57,000
 Can it make it harder to live?

797
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:03,000
 Yes, if we look at it like another thing on our to-do list, absolutely.

798
01:03:03,000 --> 01:03:07,000
 Like, I think that people can OD on pretty much anything.

799
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:10,000
 It's not just the drugs or the alcohol or whatever.

800
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:14,000
 It can be on PlayStation or it can be on personal growth.

801
01:03:14,000 --> 01:03:19,000
 There can be too much of everything.

802
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:29,000
 And I feel that the point of personal growth or self-exploration is not to reach at a certain

803
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:30,000
 destination.

804
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:34,000
 It's about learning how to enjoy that path.

805
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:43,000
 I feel that some of the most important questions that we have in life, they don't unfold in

806
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:45,000
 a shape of an answer.

807
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:48,000
 They unfold in a shape of a path.

808
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:53,000
 Can you give us an example?

809
01:03:53,000 --> 01:03:54,000
 Absolutely.

810
01:03:54,000 --> 01:04:00,000
 Let's say, I don't want to use romantic relationships because that's, you know, like everybody uses

811
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:01,000
 that.

812
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:03,000
 So let's go with family and family dynamic.

813
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:10,000
 So I will use my personal example again and say, when I was growing up, I used to describe

814
01:04:10,000 --> 01:04:15,000
 the relationship with my mom like, we're practically best friends.

815
01:04:15,000 --> 01:04:18,000
 Like we get along so well.

816
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:20,000
 It was awesome.

817
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:26,000
 And then when I grew up, I was like, maybe something's wrong with that.

818
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:28,000
 Like my mom is supposed to be my mom.

819
01:04:28,000 --> 01:04:30,000
 She's not supposed to be my best friend.

820
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:37,000
 And then we changed the dynamic because of my therapy books, coaching, et cetera, et cetera.

821
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:39,000
 It was so hard.

822
01:04:39,000 --> 01:04:47,000
 It was one of the hardest things that I've ever, ever done.

823
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:48,000
 The relationship we had before.

824
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:49,000
 It doesn't mean that it was bad.

825
01:04:49,000 --> 01:04:56,000
 It just means that when I got to this level where I'm at now, and when I became a specific

826
01:04:56,000 --> 01:05:04,000
 thing that doesn't work for me, I decided to change it and invite her into that change.

827
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:08,000
 But that doesn't mean that we still don't have the moments where I need to be very clear

828
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:11,000
 about my boundaries, about my responses.

829
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:18,000
 Like the other day she came, she doesn't live in Zagreb.

830
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:20,000
 She lives in Yapaga where I grew up.

831
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:23,000
 It's a very small village in Slavonia.

832
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:27,000
 And she brought me an early birthday present.

833
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:32,000
 She brought me red wallet, like red leather wallet.

834
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:36,000
 And I looked at it and she told me why she bought it.

835
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:38,000
 But my first thought was like, it's red.

836
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:43,000
 It's like very, very, very red, red wallet.

837
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:50,000
 And personally, I would never buy something like that for myself ever.

838
01:05:50,000 --> 01:05:52,000
 It's just not my style.

839
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:54,000
 But she told me, you know what?

840
01:05:54,000 --> 01:05:58,000
 I was reading this book about how red invites money.

841
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:00,000
 And I was like, you know what?

842
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:05,000
 Like if there's anything that I want my daughter to have to invite money, then it's a red wallet.

843
01:06:05,000 --> 01:06:08,000
 I was like, this is so sweet.

844
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:09,000
 This is awesome.

845
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:10,000
 Thank you.

846
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:16,000
 So yeah, it's not my personal preference, but that story matters more than my personal preference.

847
01:06:16,000 --> 01:06:17,000
 Do you still have it?

848
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:18,000
 Yes, absolutely.

849
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:20,000
 I wear it everywhere.

850
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:21,000
 Okay.

851
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:26,000
 So you were mentioning boundaries.

852
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:33,000
 And I heard, I hear this word often lately.

853
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:45,000
 And this is a thing that I didn't install in my life so far, or I didn't think about it consciously.

854
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:47,000
 Why do we need boundaries?

855
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:54,000
 I suppose that I have boundaries in my life, that I put them to other people also.

856
01:06:54,000 --> 01:06:57,000
 Everybody has boundaries.

857
01:06:57,000 --> 01:07:04,000
 The first one, the one that we underestimate and kind of take for granted is our skin.

858
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:06,000
 It's a literal physical boundary.

859
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:08,000
 This is how I like my skin is not your skin.

860
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:11,000
 We know that we are different from each other.

861
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:16,000
 But where it gets tricky is how do we communicate boundaries that are not so obvious?

862
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:18,000
 And what is a healthy boundary?

863
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:20,000
 How do we know that we have a healthy boundary?

864
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:25,000
 We are talking about mental emotional boundaries.

865
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:26,000
 Okay.

866
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:28,000
 How do we know that?

867
01:07:28,000 --> 01:07:33,000
 For example, someone is teasing you.

868
01:07:33,000 --> 01:07:37,000
 Someone is making fun of you.

869
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:42,000
 But in a masculine environment, that could be normal.

870
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:44,000
 And you can tease back.

871
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:47,000
 And that person can tease you back again.

872
01:07:47,000 --> 01:07:50,000
 It can go back and forth.

873
01:07:50,000 --> 01:08:05,000
 And at the moment, at one moment, one person will say, you'll lose it and start yelling or screaming or arguing with the other person.

874
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:11,000
 And this is not a good way, I suppose, to set boundaries by yelling and fighting.

875
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:20,000
 Maybe we can tell to the other person with words, with clear words, that this is just too far for us.

876
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:28,000
 But what can happen in a male environment is that they start to tease you even more when you show your weakness.

877
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:29,000
 Don't be a sissy.

878
01:08:29,000 --> 01:08:30,000
 Yes.

879
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:32,000
 When you show your weakness.

880
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:42,000
 Well, in the specific example that you use, I would love to say, well, does this go against your personal values?

881
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:50,000
 You know, because boundaries are very, like, boundary should be coming from a sense of self.

882
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:51,000
 Like, what is important to me?

883
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:53,000
 What I'm trying to protect?

884
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:55,000
 What is my peace?

885
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:08,000
 What is that center that really makes it worthy to kind of have - I'm not sure what would be the English word for that - but almost like a filter.

886
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:15,000
 How do you say those things that you have in the kitchen that you use to drain spaghetti or pasta in general?

887
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:18,000
 I have no idea what is the word, but you know what I'm referring to.

888
01:09:18,000 --> 01:09:20,000
 Yes, it's the part of the word.

889
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:22,000
 Imagine it in your mind.

890
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:24,000
 Yes, please.

891
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:31,000
 So it's that type of filter that, you know, some things will go through, but some things won't.

892
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:40,000
 An unhealthy boundary would be having either no visible distinction between where you are and where the other person is.

893
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:47,000
 So it's almost like, imagine it like a line in the sand that any wave that comes, like, it will just disappear.

894
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:56,000
 And the other version of that, but it has the same sources if you have walls build up too high so that nothing can come in.

895
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:06,000
 So that kind of middle road is where we can be connected both to ourselves and the other person at the same time.

896
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:09,000
 That's how we know the boundary is healthy.

897
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:14,000
 One more way to know if a boundary is healthy is when exactly am I setting it.

898
01:10:14,000 --> 01:10:28,000
 In your example, if the other person is already so upset and starts yelling and gets very angry and that means that the boundary should have been set way before.

899
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:43,000
 Yes, but if the person expressed the boundary, expressed himself, yeah, maybe the teasing will start to become even more aggressive.

900
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:46,000
 And then this will finish.

901
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:59,000
 I understand what you're trying to say, but here's the thing, us constantly being nice people, it's also an attempt in manipulating others.

902
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:00,000
 Okay.

903
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:12,000
 You know, like, if we are trying to be in a way that we expect a certain reaction, it doesn't matter if we're good or bad, it's still manipulation.

904
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:13,000
 How so?

905
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:18,000
 We're trying to get something out of another person.

906
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:20,000
 We are trying to get them to like us.

907
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:22,000
 We are trying to get accepted.

908
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:26,000
 We are trying to be XYZ, whatever it is.

909
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:38,000
 And that's one of the hardest things to accept that us constantly being nice and good and polite and never saying anything about what we need and what we want and what we love.

910
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:44,000
 Yes, that is a form of manipulation.

911
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:46,000
 How to balance this dance?

912
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:52,000
 So it's really a dance.

913
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:57,000
 You're trying not to stand on some other person's feet.

914
01:11:57,000 --> 01:12:04,000
 The other person is also trying that.

915
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:05,000
 And sometimes we did it.

916
01:12:05,000 --> 01:12:06,000
 We do it.

917
01:12:07,000 --> 01:12:08,000
 How to find that balance?

918
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:16,000
 We need to, I suppose, that the only answer is that we need to try and we need to experiment.

919
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:21,000
 Sometimes we will step on that foot.

920
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:28,000
 And sometimes we will see that communication and the relationship is good.

921
01:12:28,000 --> 01:12:29,000
 And we just learn.

922
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:31,000
 It's about practicing.

923
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:53,000
 What do you say to someone who is maybe a little bit too timid in relationships, very careful not to insult other person, even holding himself or herself back in relationships?

924
01:12:54,000 --> 01:12:55,000
 Where does it come from?

925
01:12:55,000 --> 01:12:57,000
 That's the first thing I would say.

926
01:12:57,000 --> 01:12:59,000
 Where did you pick up on that?

927
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:06,000
 Maybe that person was trying to not insult someone else in her life.

928
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:20,000
 But look, it's very normal that when we are meeting new people, there is almost like this testing it out phase, you know, like almost like testing the water when we are getting into the sea.

929
01:13:20,000 --> 01:13:27,000
 And we are trying to figure out, well, does it make sense to actually hang out with this person or even become something more or whatever it is.

930
01:13:27,000 --> 01:13:32,000
 And we don't, we shouldn't be underestimating that part of the process.

931
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:37,000
 It's sometimes it's our gut feeling telling us, yes, this is safe for us.

932
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:39,000
 This is okay for us.

933
01:13:39,000 --> 01:13:41,000
 Sometimes it will be not really.

934
01:13:42,000 --> 01:14:06,000
 But then if after figuring out that it is safe, we still hold back and we still try to navigate the experience through completely suppressing ourselves because of a fear of another human's reaction, then we need to ask ourselves, where did I pick up on this?

935
01:14:06,000 --> 01:14:07,000
 Where did I learn this?

936
01:14:07,000 --> 01:14:11,000
 What exactly am I afraid of?

937
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:19,000
 What exactly am I afraid to lose or to gain or what type of impression I don't want to make?

938
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:33,000
 Like, sometimes, very often, actually 99% of the cases, people actually don't want to do something, not because of the action, but because of what they think it will mean about them.

939
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:48,000
 You know, like, oh, if I set a boundary, then I will be clingy or I will be I will be someone who asks for too much or I will show that I am weak or I will be too vulnerable.

940
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:55,000
 And if I'm vulnerable, then I am not worthy or I'm complicated and nobody can deal with me and blah, blah, blah.

941
01:14:55,000 --> 01:15:00,000
 You know, like, there's like a blank line and you can fill in what feels right.

942
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:05,000
 But we attribute specific meanings to things.

943
01:15:05,000 --> 01:15:08,000
 And that's why we don't do those things.

944
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:20,000
 And then in the exploration of where we are setting the boundary, the only center that we should going back to is ourselves.

945
01:15:20,000 --> 01:15:25,000
 Like, how do I actually feel about this?

946
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:41,000
 And if we don't say it, then yes, we are trying to manage what other people think about us and we are not allowing ourselves to be fully accepted, but we are actually denying the opportunity to be fully accepted because we are not sharing it.

947
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:48,000
 You know, yes, there is vulnerability in fully saying who we are.

948
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:49,000
 Absolutely.

949
01:15:49,000 --> 01:15:56,000
 But without that vulnerability, we can't actually be accepted.

